= Walkable Compute =

'''Walkable compute''' is a Noisebridge working group / field-notes project for mobile, wearable, mostly low-desk computing rigs.

The current focus is mundane computing while standing, pacing, or walking: text editing, terminal work, reading, note-taking, messaging, lightweight development, demos, and collaborative use.

== Current status ==

We are in the '''field-report phase''': documenting what people are trying, what fails, what seems promising, and what dependencies matter.

This page is not yet an authoritative buyer’s guide. Treat it as a living compatibility guide.

== Design goals ==

* Use off-the-shelf parts where possible.
* Prefer hardware that can run free or self-sovereign software stacks.
* Keep each component substitutable: display, compute, hub, keyboard, battery, cables, mounting, and optional projection should be separately testable.
* Optimize for actual daily use: comfort, robustness, repairability, battery life, and social legibility.
* Record failures. Especially record failures. USB-C is a crime scene with marketing copy.

== Core rig shape ==

A typical experimental rig has:

# XR glasses or wearable display, mostly used as a plain display.
# Mobile compute, ideally a phone or pocket device running Linux, postmarketOS, Mobile NixOS, NixOS-derived setups, or another self-sovereign stack.
# A USB-C hub or adapter that can pass display signal, power, and input correctly.
# Split keyboard halves mounted near the hips, hanging from a belt, attached to clothing, or otherwise reachable while arms hang naturally.
# Battery pack and video-capable cables.
# Mechanical strain relief so expensive parts are not being supported by tiny USB-C ports.
# Optional projector or shared display path for socially casting a screen to nearby collaborators.

== Dependency chain ==

The most important compatibility chain is:

 compute device → USB-C / DP Alt Mode → hub or adapter → XR glasses
 battery / charger → USB-C PD input → hub → compute and/or glasses
 keyboard → Bluetooth or USB → compute
 compute device / hub → projector → nearby shared surface

A rig is only “known-good” when the whole chain works together.

A device having USB-C does '''not''' imply that it supports display output. A cable being USB-C does '''not''' imply that it carries video. A hub having many ports does '''not''' imply that it can pass display while also accepting auxiliary power and input.

