== Social norms ==

Walkable compute creates attention ambiguity. The wearer owns that ambiguity.

Default norms:

* No surprise recording.
* No surprise transcription.
* If hardware has a camera, microphone, or outward-facing sensor, disclose it plainly.
* If someone is not already opted into the experiment, assume they may interpret gaze-obscuring hardware as socially weird or surveillance-adjacent.
* When starting a conversation with someone outside the group, prefer lifting, disabling, removing, or clearly explaining the display.
* Do not make stealth the group’s social default. Stealth can be an ergonomic or aesthetic experiment; it should not be a consent hack.
* Prefer visible status conventions: display up, display down, display off, or a badge/sticker saying “display only / no camera / no recording” when true.
* Treat Noisebridge as a place to prototype openly, not to surprise-cyborg people.

== Open questions ==

* Which current XR glasses are best for boring text work?
* Which mobile Linux devices can reliably output display?
* Which hubs support video pass-through, auxiliary power, and input at the same time?
* Can a hip-mounted keyboard become socially normal enough for daily use?
* What is the least-weird attention/status protocol?
* Can a small projector reduce social ambiguity by making the screen shareable?
* How much of this should be standardized as a kit?
* What is the first rig a new participant can try without spending too much money?

